              Career in Government
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="col-md-8 px-1 mt-2 pt-2">
            <p>
              Ngozi Okonjo-Iweala served twice as Nigeria’s Finance Minister and also as
              <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minister_of_Foreign_Affairs_(Nigeria)"
                >Minister of Foreign Affairs</a
              >. During her first term as Minister of Finance under President Olusegun Obasanjo’s
              Administration, she spearheaded negotiations with the
              <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paris_Club">Paris Club</a> that led to the
              wiping out of US$30 billion of Nigeria’s debt, including the outright cancellation of
              US$18 billion. In 2003 she led efforts to improve Nigeria’s macroeconomic management
              including the implementation of an oil-price based fiscal rule where revenues accruing
              above a reference benchmark oil price were saved in a special account, “The Excess
              Crude Account” which helped to reduce macroeconomic volatility.
            </p>
