              Later Career
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="col-md-8 px-1 mt-2 pt-2 mb-5 pb-5">
            <p>
              Ngozi Okonjo-Iweala is co-Chair of the Global Commission for the Economy and Climate,
              with
              <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicholas_Stern,_Baron_Stern_of_Brentford"
                >Nicholas Stern</a
              >
              and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Polman"> Paul Polman</a>. Previously,
              she served as the co-Chair of the
              <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aid_effectiveness"
                >Global Partnership for Effective Development Cooperation</a
              >. In the past, Okonjo-Iweala was also a member of the
              <a
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Commission_on_Financing_Global_Education_Opportunity"
                >International Commission on Financing Global Education Opportunity</a
              >
              (2015-2016), chaired by
              <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gordon_Brown">Gordon Brown</a>; the Commission
              on the New Climate Economy (also co-Chaired by Paul Polman and Lord Nicholas Stern);
              the World Economic Forum Young Global Leaders Foundation;
              <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Post-2015_Development_Agenda"
                >the United Nations’ Secretary General’s High-Level Panel on the Post-2015
                Development Agenda</a
              >
              (2012-2013); and the renowned
              <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Growth_Commission">Growth Commission </a>
              (2006-2009), led by Nobel Prize winner
              <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Spence">Professor Michael Spence</a>.
              Dr. Ngozi Okonjo-Iweala is the founder of Nigeria’s first indigenous opinion-research
              organization, NOI-Polls. She also founded the
              <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ngozi_Okonjo-Iweala"
                >Center for the Study of Economies of Africa (C-SEA)</a
              >, a development research think tank based in Abuja, Nigeria’s capital and is a
              Distinguished Visiting Fellow at the Center for Global Development and the Brookings
              Institution. In 2012, Okonjo-Iweala was a candidate for President of the World Bank,
              running against
              <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dartmouth_College"> Dartmouth College</a>
              President <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jim_Yong_Kim">Jim Yong Kim</a>; if
              elected, she would have been the organization's first female president. Since 2019,
              Okonjo-Iweala has been part of
              <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UNESCO">UNESCO's</a> International Commission
              on the Futures of Education, chaired by
              <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sahle-Work_Zewde">Sahle-Work Zewde</a>. In
              2020, the
              <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Monetary_Fund"
                >International Monetary Fund's
              </a>
              Managing Director
              <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kristalina_Georgieva">Kristalina Georgieva</a>
              appointed her to an external advisory group to provide input on policy challenges.
              Also in 2020, she was appointed by the
              <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/African_Union">African Union</a> (AU) as
              special envoy to solicit international support to help the continent deal with the
              economic impact of the
              <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/COVID-19_pandemic">COVID-19 pandemic</a> . In
              June 2020,
              <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muhammadu_Buhari"
                >President Muhammadu Buhari
              </a>
              of Nigeria nominated Okonjo-Iweala as the country’s candidate to be director-general
              of the
              <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Trade_Organization"
                >World Trade Organization</a
              >
              (WTO).
            </p>
